1) Pair with Target Sum: Given a sorted array, find if there is a pair that sums up to a target value.
using System;

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 6 };
        int target = 6;
        int[] result = FindPair(numbers, target);

        if (result.Length == 2)
            Console.WriteLine($"Pair found: {result[0]}, {result[1]}");
        else
            Console.WriteLine("No pair found.");
    }

    public static int[] FindPair(int[] arr, int targetSum)
    {
        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.Length - 1;

        while (left < right)
        {
            int currentSum = arr[left] + arr[right];

            if (currentSum == targetSum)
                return new int[] { arr[left], arr[right] }; // Found the pair

            if (currentSum < targetSum)
                left++; // Need a larger sum, move left pointer right
            else
                right--; // Need a smaller sum, move right pointer left
        }

        return new int[0]; // No pair exists
    }
}

OR
using System.Linq;

public static int[] FindPairLinq(int[] arr, int targetSum)
{
    var result = arr
        .SelectMany((x, i) => arr.Skip(i + 1).Select(y => new { x, y }))
        .FirstOrDefault(p => p.x + p.y == targetSum);

    return result != null ? new int[] { result.x, result.y } : new int[0];
}

Add variation to problem
1. Return Indices instead of ValuesInstead of the numbers themselves, return the positions (indices) of the elements.
     This is tricky because if you use LINQ or sorting, you must keep track of where the numbers originally were.
2. Find All Unique PairsInstead of stopping at the first pair, find every pair that sums to the target.
    The Twist: The array might have duplicates (e.g., [1, 1, 2, 3] target 4). You have to skip used numbers to ensure the
    output doesn't have the same pair twice.
3. Find the "Closest" SumIf no pair equals the target exactly, find the pair whose sum is closest to it.
    The Logic: You still use Two-Pointers, but you keep a variable to track the minDifference found so far.
4. Triplet Sum (3Sum)Find three numbers that sum to the target.
    The Logic: You fix one number using a for loop, then use the Two-Pointer technique on the remaining part of the array
    to find the other two.
5. Triplets with Smaller SumFind the count of all triplets whose sum is less than a target value.
    The Logic: When arr[left] + arr[right] < target, it means all elements between left and right will also form a valid
    pair with arr[left] because the array is sorted.
6. Subarray Sum (Not Pairs)Find a contiguous range of numbers (like arr[2] through arr[5]) that adds up to the target.
    The Logic: This shifts from Two-Pointers to a Sliding Window approach.


